<DOC><DOCNO> AP891114-0068 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-89 1019EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-MeeseBook     11-14 0171</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Meese Book,0176</SECOND><HEAD>Former Attorney General To Publish Book to Clear His Name</HEAD><DATELINE>EDWARDSVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Former Attorney General Edwin MeeseIII says he will take the media to task for what he callsinaccurate reporting about him and the Iran-Contra affair in a bookhe is writing.   The book, to be published next year, will counter errorsreported about him during his 3{ years as the nation's topprosecutor and ``set the record straight'' on Iran-Contra, Meesesaid.   ``Some of the worst reporting was in the Iran-Contra affair,''Meese said before speaking Monday at Southern Illinois University.   About a dozen people wearing rubber pig noses demonstratedduring his appearance, chanting, ``Let's steal money. Let's telllies. Guess who we are. Meese in disguise.''   Some faculty members also protested Meese's appearance at theuniversity and the $8,000 fee for his speech.   Meese stepped down in 1988 amid allegations he had violatedethical standards in his financial affairs. Some also accused himof botching the investigation of the Iran-Contra affair.</TEXT></DOC>